                                <placeName type="parish">Llanddeti (<foreign xml:lang="cy"><ref target="https://historicplacenames.rcahmw.gov.uk/placenames/recordedname/ff45ec70-3997-4418-94b8-eab1be934f74">Llanddetty</ref></foreign>)</placeName>, <placeName type="county">Brecknockshire (<foreign xml:lang="cy"><ref target="https://historicplacenames.rcahmw.gov.uk/placenames/recordedname/6d25abb9-918e-4aca-98ce-9c921395aec5">Brycheiniog</ref></foreign>)</placeName>, <placeName type="country">Wales</placeName>
                                <geo>51.809722, -3.346017</geo>
                            <note>National Grid Reference: SO 073 132</note></origPlace>
                            <origDate notBefore="0400" notAfter="0599" precision="low" datingMethod="#julian" evidence="linguistic">Fifth or sixth century A.D.</origDate>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found" when="1695">Found on <foreign xml:lang="cy">Ystrad</foreign> mountain in Llanddeti parish. The stone and ogham inscription was recorded and sketched in 1695. The presence of ogham was first mentioned in Lhuyd's 1910 publication but the first reading of the inscription was supplied by Macalister in 1945. The stone was rediscovered again by Webley in 1957.  
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed" source="RED2007">Situated on open moorland at 455m above sea level, west of the track from Merthyr Tydfil to Talybont. The present location of the stone is high and may be the same as when it was originally described but there is a slight possibility that the stone has been moved down the hill and re-erected since it was first described (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 176).
                        </provenance>
